<subSubSection id="C33440DAFFBCBE2C34247C1BFEB3411C" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B911351FFBCBE2C34247C1BFEB3411C" blockId="16.[264,1323,1272,1819]" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C34247C1BFE644365" bold="true" box="[312,435,1352,1378]" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFBF6EA0FFBCBE2C34DF7C1AFD1B4364" author="Xue, W. Q. &amp; Wang, M. F." box="[451,716,1353,1379]" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" pagination="809 - 835" refId="ref9112" refString="Xue, W. Q., Wang, M. F. (1999) Fanniidae. In: Xue, W. Q. &amp; Chao, C. M., (Eds), Flies of China. Volume 1. [In Chinese.] Liaoning Science and Technology Press, Shenyang, pp. 809 - 835. [1996]" type="book chapter" year="1999">Xue &amp; Wang (1999)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E68D2FFBCBE2C36B87C1AFB044365" box="[932,1235,1353,1378]" class="Insecta" family="Fanniidae" genus="Piezura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pardalina" subSpecies="shanxiensis">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C36B87C1AFB044365" box="[932,1235,1353,1378]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">P. pardalina shanxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E68D2FFBCBE2C30097C1AFDF1438D" class="Insecta" family="Fanniidae" genus="Piezura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="graminicola" subSpecies="shanxiensis">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C30097C1AFDF1438D" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">P. graminicola shanxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) can be differentiated from the nominal species by a broad frons, first flagellomere mostly black, presence of dark median vittae on the abdominal tergites, and shape of the cerci. We find this list of differences puzzling because 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E68D2FFBCBE2C318A7C92FEAD4005" authority="pardalina" class="Insecta" family="Fanniidae" genus="Piezura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pardalina" subSpecies="pardalina">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C318A7C92FEAD4005" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">P. pardalina pardalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does have dark median vittae present on tergites 3–5 and the first flagellomere is weakly to moderately infuscated on the apical half. The weakly cleft mesolobus (
<figureCitation id="13150FD4FFBCBE2C31DA7F42FAF5402C" box="[1222,1314,1553,1579]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="16.[264,368,1123,1147]" captionTargetBox="[318,1245,530,1096]" captionTargetId="figure-252@16.[264,1323,499,1120]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 5. Piezura pardalina ssp. shanxiensis Xue, Wang &amp; Wu. A. Male genitalia external structures, posterior. B. Male sternite 5, ventral. (adapted from Xue &amp; Wang, 1999)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051430/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
) is a feature that we have observed in a few specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E68D2FFBCBE2C36B97F6AFB784055" authority="pardalina" box="[933,1199,1593,1618]" class="Insecta" family="Fanniidae" genus="Piezura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pardalina" subSpecies="pardalina">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C36B97F6AFB784055" box="[933,1199,1593,1618]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">P. pardalina pardalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13150FD4FFBCBE2C31A37F6AFAC94054" box="[1215,1310,1593,1619]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="13.[264,368,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[293,1313,770,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-128@13.[264,1323,748,1740]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 4. Piezura pardalina ssp. pardalina Rondani. A. Male genitalia external structures, posterior. B. Male mesolobus, variant form. C. Female spermatheca. D. Female genitalia, ventral. E. Male sternite 5, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051426/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Consequently, the only features that differentiate this subspecies from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E68D2FFBCBE2C318E7F32FEAD40A5" authority="pardalina" class="Insecta" family="Fanniidae" genus="Piezura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="pardalina" subSpecies="pardalina">
<emphasis id="B95ACF43FFBCBE2C318E7F32FEAD40A5" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="57">P. pardalina pardalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the width of the frontal vitta and the infuscation pattern of the first flagellomere. As no material of this subspecies was available for examination, we do not feel that there is sufficient evidence at this time to synonymize this taxon with the nominal species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
